{
    "level": "A2",
    "intro": "In this topic you will learn to use <strong>some people, any people, no people</strong> and related pronoun forms without common mistakes.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "STATEMENTS",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "<strong>Some people</strong> is the usual choice in affirmative sentences:",
            "example": "Some people work better at night."
        },
        {
            "label": "QUESTIONS / NEGATIVES",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "<strong>Any people</strong> usually appears in questions and negatives:",
            "example": "Do you know any people here?"
        },
        {
            "label": "NEGATIVE IDEA",
            "color": "rose",
            "text": "<strong>No people</strong> or <strong>nobody / no one</strong> already carry the negative meaning:",
            "example": "No people were waiting outside."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Core patterns",
    "intro": "Compare the most common patterns with <strong>people</strong> and related pronouns.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Affirmative",
            "title": "some people",
            "subtitle": "an unspecified part of a group: Some people need more time."
        },
        {
            "label": "Question / negative",
            "title": "any people",
            "subtitle": "Do you know any people there?"
        },
        {
            "label": "Full negative",
            "title": "no people",
            "subtitle": "No people came to the meeting."
        },
        {
            "label": "Pronoun form",
            "title": "someone / anyone / no one",
            "subtitle": "Someone is at the door."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. How it works in sentences",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Statements with some people",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "<strong>Some people</strong> sounds natural when you mean an unspecified part of a larger group.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Some people learn faster with examples.",
                    "ua": "Some people learn faster with examples."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Some people in my class already have jobs.",
                    "ua": "Some people in my class already have jobs."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Some people just prefer quiet cafés.",
                    "ua": "Some people simply prefer quiet cafés."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Questions and negatives with any people",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "In neutral questions and negatives, <strong>any people</strong> is usually the better choice.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Do you know any people in Warsaw?",
                    "ua": "Do you know any people in Warsaw?"
                },
                {
                    "en": "I do not know any people on this street.",
                    "ua": "I do not know any people on this street."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Are there any people in the office now?",
                    "ua": "Are there any people in the office now?"
                }
            ],
            "note": "If you expect a positive answer, <strong>some people</strong> can appear in a question."
        },
        {
            "label": "No people and pronoun forms",
            "color": "rose",
            "description": "<strong>No people</strong>, <strong>nobody</strong>, and <strong>no one</strong> are already negative on their own.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "No people were sitting outside.",
                    "ua": "No people were sitting outside."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Nobody answered the phone.",
                    "ua": "Nobody answered the phone."
                },
                {
                    "en": "No one wanted to leave early.",
                    "ua": "No one wanted to leave early."
                }
            ],
            "note": "Do not add another <strong>not</strong>: not <span class=\"line-through\">I do not know nobody</span>."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. Common mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Mistake 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Using some in a neutral question.",
            "wrong": "Do you know some people here?",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">Do you know any people here?</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Double negative.",
            "wrong": "I do not know no people there.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">I do not know any people there.</span> / <span class=\"font-mono\">I know no people there.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "Wrong agreement with people.",
            "wrong": "Some people is waiting outside.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">Some people are waiting outside.</span>"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "4. Quick summary",
    "items": [
        "<strong>Some people</strong> is the normal choice in affirmative sentences.",
        "<strong>Any people</strong> is typical in questions and negatives.",
        "<strong>No people</strong>, <strong>nobody</strong>, and <strong>no one</strong> already contain the negative idea.",
        "With <strong>people</strong>, the verb is usually plural: <em>people are</em>.",
        "Avoid double negatives: <em>I do not know anybody</em> or <em>I know nobody</em>."
    ]
}

